main_text: 🍅 #pomegranate ❤️ ‘What is the structure and pharmacology of punicalagin?’ Thanks @amirhosein_firouzi_ for the great question! Punica granatum is a deciduous shrub native to the Middle East but is now grown around the world for its delicious fruit the pomegranate pictured above. Pomegranates contain a wide range of health-promoting compounds (swipe!) including a class of hydrolyzable ellagitannins polyphenols of which punicalagin pictured above is a member. Polyphenols are thought to protect plant tissues from ultraviolet radiation via the phenolic antioxidant mechanism (swipe!): hydroxyl groups oxidize and neutralize dangerous free radicals via quinone reduction. Punicalagin is an extensively hydroxylated polyphenol making it a potent antioxidant. In addition the glucose can be hydrolyzed and punicalagin can be metabolized into urolithins in the colon (swipe!) increasing the available oxidizing groups and total antioxidant capacity. Oxidative stress (swipe!) is one of the major pathological mechanisms involved in many types of diseases and conditions (swipe!). Often there is more information on clinical outcomes than mechanism of action because the money is in marketing and not in understanding. We don’t exactly know how antioxidants can combat certain diseases but we do know that fruits and vegetables and plant-based diets are full of antioxidants! Do you like pomegranate? Discuss in the comments below!PHOTO: Fahmy et al 2020 Venusova et al 2021.*************************************************Submit your questions on the chemistry of nature to @natural.products.lab🌱—————————————————————#naturalproductschemistry #microbiology #naturalproductslab #naturalproducts #biodiversity #medicinalplants #chemistry #chemistryiscool #neature #science #herbs #medicine #scicomm #pharmacognosy #pharma #pharmacology #naturalchemistry #laboratory #research #nature#staycurious 💫

.
Eating a pomegranate is one messy ordeal. Rouge juices from de-seeding the tiny kernels will almost 𝙖𝙡𝙬𝙖𝙮𝙨 find a way to land onto any light coloured clothing.

But once you’ve managed to remove all the seeds  they make for a great addition to dishes and desserts!

This is a coconutty chocolately tart - in both the crust and filling  with a generous sprinkle of pomegranate on top for some contrast in texture and flavour. The little red beads give that bright juicy bursts and help to cut the sweetness and richness of the chocolate.

𝘿𝙤 𝙮𝙤𝙪 𝙝𝙖𝙫𝙚 𝙖 𝙜𝙤-𝙩𝙤 𝙢𝙚𝙩𝙝𝙤𝙙 𝙛𝙤𝙧 𝙧𝙚𝙢𝙤𝙫𝙞𝙣𝙜 𝙥𝙤𝙢𝙚𝙜𝙧𝙖𝙣𝙖𝙩𝙚 𝙨𝙚𝙚𝙙𝙨?

[ ʀᴇᴄɪᴘᴇ ] ꜰᴏʀ 8" ᴛᴀʀᴛ ᴏʀ 14"x5" ʀᴇᴄᴛᴀɴɢᴜʟᴀʀ ᴛᴀʀᴛ ᴘᴀɴ
🥥 ᴄʜᴏᴄᴏ ᴄᴏᴄᴏɴᴜᴛ ᴄʀᴜꜱᴛ 🥥
1/2 cup (sweetened) shredded coconut toasted
1 cup AP flour
2 tbsp cocoa powder
8 tbsp (113g) cold unsalted butter  in chunks
1/4 cup powdered sugar (can inc to 1/3 cup if using unsweetened coconut flakes)
1/2 tsp salt

1. Pulse everything in a food processor until a dough/ball forms.
2. Press into a pie tart & freeze for 10 mins.
3. Bake @ 350F for 20mins until golden. Then cool before using.

Who here loves pomegranates? Here is another amazing reason to devour them regularly! Pomegranates have been a symbol of fertility in Zoroastrian and other ancient cultures. 🤰No wonder - the structure of the pomegranate (and the look of it opened) has a strong resemblance to a female ovary.⁠⁠However it’s not just the look of it - scientists have now discovered that pomegranates contain a form of female hormone oestrogen - called estrone - that is similar in function and structure to the one found in mammals. It is even believed that pomegranates are the richest source of it found in nature.⁠🌱⁠⁠A 2004 study published in the Journal of Ethnopharmacology showed that pomegranates can help alleviate hormonal symptoms related to low oestrogen levels.⁠⁠Low oestrogen is often associated with issues in women such as low energy and fatigue acne abnormal facial and body hair as well as hot flushes and other symptoms of perimenopause.⁠⁠More good news is that unlike synthetic sources and some bioidentical sources of oestrogen - pomegranate does not have any of their potentially carcinogenic effects. ✊ On the contrary - it acts as an adaptogen enhancing the levels of estrogen when it is low but blocking stronger estrogens if levels are excessive.⁠⁠According to GreenMedInfo:⁠⁠“In an August 2011 study published in the Journal of Nutritional Biochemistry pomegranate extract was compared to the drugs Tamoxifen (T) and Estradiol (E) and was shown to prevent activity associated with estrogen-dependent cancer promotion without increasing the weight of the uterus a well known indicator of the potential carcinogenicity of (T) and (E)“.⁠⁠How to enjoy it?⁠❤️ Eat the seeds whole (yep they can be eaten whole!)⁠❤️Drink it as a juice - but make sure it’s pure and without the additives⁠❤️ For a powerful anti-ageing and antioxidant drink blend pomegranate juice with 1 tsp acai powder⁠What are your favourite ways to eat a pomegranate? Share with us below!⁠⁠Credit : @organicburst 🙏👍Please DM for credit or removal#pomegranate #hormones #hormonebalance #womenshealth #sideeffects

{"1": {"comment_id": "naturethecure"  "comment_text": "Who here loves pomegranates? Here is another amazing reason to devour them regularly! Pomegranates have been a symbol of fertility in Zoroastrian and other ancient cultures. 🤰No wonder - the structure of the pomegranate (and the look of it opened) has a strong resemblance to a female ovary.⁠
⁠
However  it’s not just the look of it - scientists have now discovered that pomegranates contain a form of female hormone oestrogen - called estrone - that is similar in function and structure to the one found in mammals. It is even believed that pomegranates are the richest source of it found in nature.⁠🌱⁠
⁠
A 2004 study published in the Journal of Ethnopharmacology showed that pomegranates can help alleviate hormonal symptoms related to low oestrogen levels.⁠
⁠
Low oestrogen is often associated with issues in women such as low energy and fatigue  acne  abnormal facial and body hair  as well as hot flushes and other symptoms of perimenopause.⁠
⁠
More good news is that unlike synthetic sources and some bioidentical sources of oestrogen - pomegranate does not have any of their potentially carcinogenic effects. ✊ On the contrary - it acts as an adaptogen  enhancing the levels of estrogen when it is low but blocking stronger estrogens if levels are excessive.⁠
⁠
According to GreenMedInfo:⁠
⁠
“In an August 2011 study published in the Journal of Nutritional Biochemistry  pomegranate extract was compared to the drugs Tamoxifen (T) and Estradiol (E) and was shown to prevent activity associated with estrogen-dependent cancer promotion  without increasing the weight of the uterus  a well known indicator of the potential carcinogenicity of (T) and (E)“.⁠
⁠
How to enjoy it?⁠
❤️ Eat the seeds whole (yep  they can be eaten whole!)⁠
❤️Drink it as a juice - but make sure it’s pure and without the additives⁠
❤️ For a powerful anti-ageing and antioxidant drink blend pomegranate juice with 1 tsp acai powder
⁠
What are your favourite ways to eat a pomegranate? Share with us below!⁠
⁠

Pomegranate Cinnamon Ginger Punch ☘😇😋Pomegranate☘ - Pomegranate is loaded with antioxidants. It is believed that pomegranate has three times more antioxidants than red wine and green tea. It is low in calories and high in fibre vitamins and minerals. This fruit juice can help remove free radicals protect cells from damage and reduce inflammation. The antioxidants in the juice stall the progression of Alzheimer disease and protect memory. It also promotes healthy gut bacteria and reduces inflammation in the digestive tract. Its high fibre properties serve as fuel for probiotics and helps prevent certain digestive health conditions.Cinnamon☘ -Cinnamon contains large amounts of highly potent polyphenol antioxidants. main_text: #Pomegranate and #Apple in #RoseWater with added #Coconut-sugar This is a spin off of a persian summer treat called #Faloodehseeb It is such a #refreshing-dessert . I diced apple (traditionally is grated). Then I added pomegranate with about a 1/2 ounce of rosewater. The pomegranate was frozen (the traditional dish is always served chilled or with added ice) I added coconut sugar but any sweetener will do. Normally lemon or lime is juice is also added. You can serve it in a cocktail glass or small bowl. Share your take on how you would serve it below.Enjoy 😉

comment:
{"1": {"comment_id": "healthy.by.bri"  "comment_text": "PSYLLIUM HUSK OATS

As you already know  I fell deeply in love with psyllium husks in my porridge. So delicious plus it makes me full for hours!

I N G R E D I E N T S
• 40g oats
• 1 tsp chia seeds (optional)
• 1 tsp flaxseeds (optional)
• 1-2 tsp psyllium husk
• vanilla extract
• lots of water
• toppings (I used granola  orange  pomegranate seeds  vegan yogurt & the @myrawjoy salted carawmel & pecan cookie *crumbled)

I N S T R U C T I O N S
• bring oats  chia seeds  flaxseeds and vanilla extract with some water to boil
• stir in psyllium husk and add more water until you like the texture (note that psyllium husk soak up a lot of water)
• ENJOY

________________________________________
